# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: online-algorithms
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:online-algorithms/adversary-online-algorithm] In computer science, an online algorithm measures its competitiveness against different **adversary models**.
[src:online-algorithms/adversary-online-algorithm] For deterministic algorithms, the adversary is the same as the adaptive offline adversary.
[src:online-algorithms/adversary-online-algorithm] For randomized online algorithms competitiveness can depend upon the adversary model used.
[src:online-algorithms/adversary-online-algorithm] The three common adversaries are the oblivious adversary, the adaptive online adversary, and the adaptive offline adversary.
[src:online-algorithms/adversary-online-algorithm] The **oblivious adversary** is sometimes referred to as the weak adversary.
[src:online-algorithms/adversary-online-algorithm] This adversary knows the algorithm's code, but does not get to know the randomized results of the algorithm.
[src:online-algorithms/adversary-online-algorithm] The **adaptive online adversary** is sometimes called the medium adversary.
[src:online-algorithms/adversary-online-algorithm] This adversary must make its own decision before it is allowed to know the decision of the algorithm.
[src:online-algorithms/adversary-online-algorithm] The **adaptive offline adversary** is sometimes called the strong adversary.
[src:online-algorithms/adversary-online-algorithm] This adversary knows everything, even the random number generator.
[src:online-algorithms/adversary-online-algorithm] This adversary is so strong that randomization does not help against it.
[src:online-algorithms/competitive-analysis-online-algorithm] For many algorithms, performance is dependent not only on the size of the inputs, but also on their values.
[src:online-algorithms/competitive-analysis-online-algorithm] For example, sorting an array of elements varies in difficulty depending on the initial order.
[src:online-algorithms/competitive-analysis-online-algorithm] Such data-dependent algorithms are analysed for average-case and worst-case data.
[src:online-algorithms/competitive-analysis-online-algorithm] Competitive analysis is a way of doing worst case analysis for on-line and randomized algorithms, which are typically data dependent.
[src:online-algorithms/competitive-analysis-online-algorithm] In competitive analysis, one imagines an "adversary" which deliberately chooses difficult data, to maximize the ratio of the cost of the algorithm being studied and some optimal algorithm.
[src:online-algorithms/competitive-analysis-online-algorithm] For example, the quicksort algorithm chooses one element, called the "pivot", that is, on average, not too far from the center value of the data being sorted.
[src:online-algorithms/competitive-analysis-online-algorithm] Quicksort then separates the data into two piles, one of which contains all elements with value less than the value of the pivot, and the other containing the rest of the elements.
[src:online-algorithms/competitive-analysis-online-algorithm] If quicksort chooses the pivot in some deterministic fashion (for instance, always choosing the first element in the list), then it is easy for an adversary to arrange the data beforehand so that quicksort will perform in worst-case time.
[src:online-algorithms/competitive-analysis-online-algorithm] If, however, quicksort chooses some random element to be the pivot, then an adversary without knowledge of what random numbers are coming up cannot arrange the data to guarantee worst-case execution time for quicksort.
[src:online-algorithms/competitive-analysis-online-algorithm] (Typically, the cost of accessing an item is equal to its position in the list.) After an access, the list may be rearranged.
[src:online-algorithms/competitive-analysis-online-algorithm] The *Move-To-Front algorithm* simply moves the requested item to the front after the access, at no cost.
[src:online-algorithms/competitive-analysis-online-algorithm] The *Transpose algorithm* swaps the accessed item with the item immediately before it, also at no cost.
[src:online-algorithms/competitive-analysis-online-algorithm] Classical methods of analysis showed that Transpose is optimal in certain contexts.
[src:online-algorithms/competitive-analysis-online-algorithm] In practice, Move-To-Front performed much better.
[src:online-algorithms/competitive-analysis-online-algorithm] Competitive analysis was used to show that an adversary can make Transpose perform arbitrarily badly compared to an optimal algorithm, whereas Move-To-Front can never be made to incur more than twice the cost of an optimal algorithm.
[src:online-algorithms/competitive-analysis-online-algorithm] In the case of online requests from a server, competitive algorithms are used to overcome uncertainties about the future.
[src:online-algorithms/competitive-analysis-online-algorithm] That is, the algorithm does not "know" the future, while the imaginary adversary (the "competitor") "knows".
[src:online-algorithms/competitive-analysis-online-algorithm] Similarly, competitive algorithms were developed for distributed systems, where the algorithm has to react to a request arriving at one location, without "knowing" what has just happened in a remote location.
[src:online-algorithms/competitive-analysis-online-algorithm] This setting was presented in (Awerbuch, Kutten & Peleg 1992).
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] The ***k*-server problem** is a problem of theoretical computer science in the category of online algorithms, one of two abstract problems on metric spaces that are central to the theory of competitive analysis (the other being metrical task systems).
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] In this problem, an online algorithm must control the movement of a set of *k* *servers*, represented as points in a metric space, and handle *requests* that are also in the form of points in the space.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] As each request arrives, the algorithm must determine which server to move to the requested point.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] The goal of the algorithm is to keep the total distance all servers move small, relative to the total distance the servers could have moved by an optimal adversary who knows in advance the entire sequence of requests.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] The problem was first posed by Mark Manasse, Lyle A.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] The most prominent open question concerning the *k*-server problem is the so-called *k*-server conjecture, also posed by Manasse et al.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] This conjecture states that there is an algorithm for solving the *k*-server problem in an arbitrary metric space and for any number *k* of servers that has competitive ratio exactly *k*.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] Manasse et al. were able to prove their conjecture when *k* = 2, and for more general values of *k* for some metric spaces restricted to have exactly *k*+1 points.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] Larmore (1991) proved the conjecture for tree metrics.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] The special case of metrics in which all distances are equal is called the *paging problem* because it models the problem of page replacement algorithms in memory caches, and was also already known to have a *k*-competitive algorithm (Sleator and Tarjan 1985).
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] (1990) first proved that there exists an algorithm with finite competitive ratio for any constant *k* and any metric space, and finally Koutsoupias and Papadimitriou (1995) proved that Work Function Algorithm (WFA) has competitive ratio 2*k* - 1.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] However, despite the efforts of many other researchers, reducing the competitive ratio to *k* or providing an improved lower bound remains open as of 2014.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] The most common believed scenario is that the Work Function Algorithm is *k*-competitive.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] To this direction, in 2000 Bartal and Koutsoupias showed that this is true for some special cases (if the metric space is a line, a weighted star or any metric of *k*+2 points).
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] The *k*-server conjecture has also a version for randomized algorithms, which asks if there exists a randomized algorithm with competitive ratio O(log *k*) in any arbitrary metric space (with at least *k* + 1 points).
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] In 2011, a randomized algorithm with competitive bound Õ(log2k log3n) was found.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] In 2017, a randomized algorithm with competitive bound O(log6 k) was announced, but was later retracted.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] In 2022 it was shown that the randomized version of the conjecture is false.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] To make the problem more concrete, imagine sending customer support technicians to customers when they have trouble with their equipment.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] In our example problem there are two technicians, Mary and Noah, serving three customers, in San Francisco, California; Washington, DC; and Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] As a *k*-server problem, the servers are the technicians, so *k* = 2 and this is a 2-server problem.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] Washington and Baltimore are 35 miles (56 km) apart, while San Francisco is 3,000 miles (4,800 km) away from both, and initially Mary and Noah are both in San Francisco.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] Then, our algorithm will assign one of the servers (say Mary) to the Washington area, after which she will always be the closest server and always be assigned to all customer requests.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] Thus, every day our algorithm incurs the cost of traveling between Washington and Baltimore and back, 70 miles (110 km).
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] After a year of this request pattern, the algorithm will have incurred 20,500 miles (33,000 km) travel: 3,000 to send Mary to the East Coast, and 17,500 for the trips between Washington and Baltimore.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] On the other hand, an optimal adversary who knows the future request schedule could have sent both Mary and Noah to Washington and Baltimore respectively, paying 6,000 miles (9,700 km) of travel once but then avoiding any future travel costs.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] The competitive ratio of our algorithm on this input is 20,500/6,000 or approximately 3.4, and by adjusting the parameters of this example the competitive ratio of this algorithm can be made arbitrarily large.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] Thus we see that always assigning the closest server can be far from optimal.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] On the other hand, it seems foolish for an algorithm that does not know future requests to send both of its technicians away from San Francisco, as the next request could be in that city and it would have to send someone back immediately.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] So it seems that it is difficult or impossible for a *k*-server algorithm to perform well relative to its adversary.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] However, for the 2-server problem, there exists an algorithm that always has a total travel distance of at most twice the adversary's distance.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] The *k*-server conjecture states that similar solutions exist for problems with any larger number of technicians.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] The k-server problem is also useful in an offline setting, that is, when the sequence of requests is completely known.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] For examples, for some algorithms the sequence of memory accesses is independent of the input (an example is matrix multiplication), and so the paging problem can be solved offline.
[src:online-algorithms/k-server-problem] This problem has been shown to be solvable in polynomial time.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] The **List Update** or the **List Access** problem is a simple model used in the study of competitive analysis of online algorithms.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] Given a set of items in a list where the cost of accessing an item is proportional to its distance from the head of the list, e.g. a linked List, and a request sequence of accesses, the problem is to come up with a strategy of reordering the list so that the total cost of accesses is minimized.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] The reordering can be done at any time but incurs a cost.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] Along with its original uses, this problem has been suggested to have a strong similarity to problems of improving global context and compressibility following a Burrows–Wheeler transform.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] Following this transform, files tend to have large regions with locally high frequencies, and compression efficiency is greatly improved by techniques that tend to move frequently-occurring characters toward zero, or the front of the "list".
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] Due to this, methods and variants of Move-to-Front and frequency counts often follow the BWT algorithm to improve compressibility.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] An adversary is an entity that gets to choose the request sequence $\sigma$ for an algorithm *ALG*.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] Depending on whether $\sigma$ can be changed based on the strategy of *ALG*, adversaries are given various powers, and the performance of *ALG* is measured against these adversaries.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] An **adaptive online adversary** gets to make the next request based on the previous results of the online algorithm, but pays for the request optimally and online.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] An **adaptive offline adversary** gets to make the next request based on the previous results of the online algorithm, but pays the optimal offline cost.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] Competitive analysis for many list update problems were carried out without any specific knowledge of the exact nature of the optimum offline algorithm (OPT).
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] There is an algorithm that runs in O(*n*2*m*(*m*-1)!) time and O(*m*!) space where *n* is the length of the request sequence and *m* is the length of the list.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] The best known optimal offline algorithm dependent on request sequence length runs in O(m^2(m−1)!n) time claimed by Dr Srikrishnan Divakaran in 2014.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] Paid transpositions are in general necessary for optimum algorithms.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] Consider a list (*a*,*b*,*c*) where *a* is at the head of the list, and a request sequence *c*,*b*,*c*,*b*.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] An optimal offline algorithm using only free exchanges would cost 9 (3+3+2+1), whereas an optimal offline algorithm using only paid exchanges would cost 8.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] So, we cannot get away with just using free transpositions for the optimum offline algorithm.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] The optimum list update problem was proven to be NP-hard by (Ambühl 2000).
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] An online algorithm *ALG* has a competitive ratio *c* if for any input it performs at least as good as *c* times worse than OPT. i.e. if there exists an $\alpha \geq 0$ such that for all finite length request sequences $\sigma$ , $ALG(\sigma )-c.OPT(\sigma )\leq \alpha$ .
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] Online algorithms can either be deterministic or randomized and it turns out that randomization in this case can truly help against oblivious adversaries.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] After accessing an item, transpose it with the immediately preceding item.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] For each item maintain a frequency count of the number of accesses to it - when an element is accessed increase its frequency count and reorder the list in the decreasing order of frequencies.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] Observe that all these use just free transpositions.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] It turns out that both TRANS and FC are not competitive.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] In a classic result using Potential method analysis (Sleator & Tarjan 1985) proved that MTF is 2-competitive.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] The proof does not require the explicit knowledge of OPT but instead counts the number of inversions i.e. elements occurring in opposite order in the lists of MTF and OPT.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] Any deterministic algorithm has a lower bound of $2-{\frac {2}{l+1}}$ for a list of length *l*, and MTF is actually the optimum deterministic list update algorithm.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] The type of adversary doesn't matter in the case of deterministic algorithms, because the adversary can run a copy of the deterministic algorithm on their own to precompute the most disastrous sequence.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] For every item in the list, maintain a bit.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] Initialize all the bits uniformly and randomly to 0 or 1.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] When an item is accessed, flip the bit, and if it is 1 move it to the front, else don't.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] This algorithm is barely random - it makes all its random choices in the beginning and not during the run.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] It turns out that BIT breaks the deterministic bound - it is **better** than MTF against oblivious adversaries.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] There are other randomized algorithms that perform better than BIT.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] In 1995, a randomized algorithm with competitive ratio of 1.6 was presented by Albers et al.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] Boris Teia proved a lower bound of 1.5 for any randomized list update algorithm.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] The list update problem where elements maybe inserted and deleted is called the dynamic list update problem, as opposed to the static list update problem where only accessing list elements are allowed.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] The lower bound of $2-{\frac {2}{l+1}}$ holds for the dynamic model as well.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] There are different cost models as well.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] In the usual full cost model, an access to an element located at a position *i* costs *i*, but the last comparison is inevitable for any algorithm, i.e. there are *i-1* elements standing in the way of *i*.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] In the partial cost model, these final comparison costs totaling to the number of elements in the request sequence are ignored.
[src:online-algorithms/list-update-problem] For the costs of paid transpositions other than unity, **P****d** models are used.
[src:online-algorithms/online-algorithm] In computer science, an **online algorithm** is one that can process its input piece-by-piece in a serial fashion, i.e., in the order that the input is fed to the algorithm, without having the entire input available from the start.
[src:online-algorithms/online-algorithm] In contrast, an **offline algorithm** is given the whole problem data from the beginning and is required to output an answer which solves the problem at hand.
[src:online-algorithms/online-algorithm] In operations research, the area in which online algorithms are developed is called online optimization.
[src:online-algorithms/online-algorithm] As an example, consider the sorting algorithms selection sort and insertion sort: selection sort repeatedly selects the minimum element from the unsorted remainder and places it at the front, which requires access to the entire input; it is thus an offline algorithm.
[src:online-algorithms/online-algorithm] On the other hand, insertion sort considers one input element per iteration and produces a partial solution without considering future elements.
[src:online-algorithms/online-algorithm] Thus insertion sort is an online algorithm.
[src:online-algorithms/online-algorithm] Note that the final result of an insertion sort is optimum, i.e., a correctly sorted list.
[src:online-algorithms/online-algorithm] For many problems, online algorithms cannot match the performance of offline algorithms.
[src:online-algorithms/online-algorithm] If the ratio between the performance of an online algorithm and an optimal offline algorithm is bounded, the online algorithm is called competitive.
[src:online-algorithms/online-algorithm] Not every *offline algorithm* has an efficient *online* counterpart.
[src:online-algorithms/online-algorithm] In grammar theory they are associated with Straight-line grammars.
[src:online-algorithms/online-algorithm] Because it does not know the whole input, an online algorithm is forced to make decisions that may later turn out not to be optimal, and the study of online algorithms has focused on the quality of decision-making that is possible in this setting.
[src:online-algorithms/online-algorithm] Competitive analysis formalizes this idea by comparing the relative performance of an online and offline algorithm for the same problem instance.
[src:online-algorithms/online-algorithm] Specifically, the competitive ratio of an algorithm, is defined as the worst-case ratio of its cost divided by the optimal cost, over all possible inputs.
[src:online-algorithms/online-algorithm] The competitive ratio of an online problem is the best competitive ratio achieved by an online algorithm.
[src:online-algorithms/online-algorithm] Intuitively, the competitive ratio of an algorithm gives a measure on the quality of solutions produced by this algorithm, while the competitive ratio of a problem shows the importance of knowing the future for this problem.
[src:online-algorithms/online-algorithm] A problem exemplifying the concepts of online algorithms is the Canadian traveller problem.
[src:online-algorithms/online-algorithm] The goal of this problem is to minimize the cost of reaching a target in a weighted graph where some of the edges are unreliable and may have been removed from the graph.
[src:online-algorithms/online-algorithm] However, that an edge has been removed (*failed*) is only revealed to *the traveller* when she/he reaches one of the edge's endpoints.
[src:online-algorithms/online-algorithm] The worst case for this problem is simply that all of the unreliable edges fail and the problem reduces to the usual shortest path problem.
[src:online-algorithms/online-algorithm] An alternative analysis of the problem can be made with the help of competitive analysis.
[src:online-algorithms/online-algorithm] For this method of analysis, the offline algorithm knows in advance which edges will fail and the goal is to minimize the ratio between the online and offline algorithms' performance.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] In a computer operating system that uses paging for virtual memory management, **page replacement algorithms** decide which memory pages to page out, sometimes called swap out, or write to disk, when a page of memory needs to be allocated.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Page replacement happens when a requested page is not in memory (page fault) and a free page cannot be used to satisfy the allocation, either because there are none, or because the number of free pages is lower than some threshold.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] When the page that was selected for replacement and paged out is referenced again it has to be paged in (read in from disk), and this involves waiting for I/O completion.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] This determines the *quality* of the page replacement algorithm: the less time waiting for page-ins, the better the algorithm.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The page replacing problem is a typical online problem from the competitive analysis perspective in the sense that the optimal deterministic algorithm is known.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Page replacement algorithms were a hot topic of research and debate in the 1960s and 1970s.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] That mostly ended with the development of sophisticated LRU (least recently used) approximations and working set algorithms.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Since then, some basic assumptions made by the traditional page replacement algorithms were invalidated, resulting in a revival of research.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Requirements for page replacement algorithms have changed due to differences in operating system kernel architectures.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] In particular, most modern OS kernels have unified virtual memory and file system caches, requiring the page replacement algorithm to select a page from among the pages of both user program virtual address spaces and cached files.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The latter pages have specific properties.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] For example, they can be locked, or can have write ordering requirements imposed by journaling.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Moreover, as the goal of page replacement is to minimize total time waiting for memory, it has to take into account memory requirements imposed by other kernel sub-systems that allocate memory.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] As a result, page replacement in modern kernels (Linux, FreeBSD, and Solaris) tends to work at the level of a general purpose kernel memory allocator, rather than at the higher level of a virtual memory subsystem.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] When a process incurs a page fault, a local page replacement algorithm selects for replacement some page that belongs to that same process (or a group of processes sharing a memory partition).
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] A global replacement algorithm is free to select any page in memory.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Local page replacement assumes some form of memory partitioning that determines how many pages are to be assigned to a given process or a group of processes.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Most popular forms of partitioning are *fixed partitioning* and *balanced set* algorithms based on the working set model.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The advantage of local page replacement is its scalability: each process can handle its page faults independently, leading to more consistent performance for that process.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] However global page replacement is more efficient on an overall system basis.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Modern general purpose computers and some embedded processors have support for virtual memory.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] In most of them, each process has its own virtual address space.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] A page table maps a subset of the process virtual addresses to physical addresses.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] In addition, in most architectures the page table holds an "access" bit and a "dirty" bit for each page in the page table.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The CPU sets the access bit when the process reads or writes memory in that page.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The CPU sets the dirty bit when the process writes memory in that page.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The operating system can modify the access and dirty bits.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Most replacement algorithms simply return the target page as their result.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] This means that if target page is *dirty* (that is, contains data that have to be written to the stable storage before page can be reclaimed), I/O has to be initiated to send that page to the stable storage (to *clean* the page).
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] In the early days of virtual memory, time spent on cleaning was not of much concern, because virtual memory was first implemented on systems with full duplex channels to the stable storage, and cleaning was customarily overlapped with paging.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Contemporary commodity hardware, on the other hand, does not support full duplex transfers, and cleaning of target pages becomes an issue.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] To deal with this situation, various *precleaning* policies are implemented.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Precleaning is the mechanism that starts I/O on dirty pages that are (likely) to be replaced soon.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The idea is that by the time the precleaned page is actually selected for the replacement, the I/O will complete and the page will be clean.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Precleaning assumes that it is possible to identify pages that will be replaced *next*.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Precleaning that is too eager can waste I/O bandwidth by writing pages that manage to get re-dirtied before being selected for replacement.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The (h,k)-paging problem is a generalization of the model of paging problem: Let h,k be positive integers such that $h\leq k$ .
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] We measure the performance of an algorithm with cache of size $h\leq k$ relative to the theoretically optimal page replacement algorithm.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] If $h<k$ , we provide the optimal page replacement algorithm with strictly less resource.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The (h,k)-paging problem is a way to measure how an online algorithm performs by comparing it with the performance of the optimal algorithm, specifically, separately parameterizing the cache size of the online algorithm and optimal algorithm.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Marking algorithms is a general class of paging algorithms.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] For each page, we associate it with a bit called its mark.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Initially, we set all pages as unmarked.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] During a stage (a period of operation or a sequence of requests) of page requests, we mark a page when it is first requested in this stage.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] A marking algorithm is such an algorithm that never pages out a marked page.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] If ALG is a marking algorithm with a cache of size k, and OPT is the optimal algorithm with a cache of size h, where $h\leq k$ , then ALG is ${\tfrac {k}{k-h+1}}$ -competitive.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] So every marking algorithm attains the ${\tfrac {k}{k-h+1}}$ -competitive ratio.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] LRU is a marking algorithm while FIFO is not a marking algorithm.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] An algorithm is conservative, if on any consecutive request sequence containing k or fewer distinct page references, the algorithm will incur k or fewer page faults.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] If ALG is a conservative algorithm with a cache of size k, and OPT is the optimal algorithm with a cache of $h\leq k$ , then ALG is ${\tfrac {k}{k-h+1}}$ -competitive.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] So every conservative algorithm attains the ${\tfrac {k}{k-h+1}}$ -competitive ratio.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] LRU, FIFO and CLOCK are conservative algorithms.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] For example, a page that is not going to be used for the next 6 seconds will be swapped out over a page that is going to be used within the next 0.4 seconds.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Despite this limitation, algorithms exist that can offer near-optimal performance — the operating system keeps track of all pages referenced by the program, and it uses those data to decide which pages to swap in and out on subsequent runs.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] This algorithm can offer near-optimal performance, but not on the first run of a program, and only if the program's memory reference pattern is relatively consistent each time it runs.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Analysis of the paging problem has also been done in the field of online algorithms.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Efficiency of randomized online algorithms for the paging problem is measured using amortized analysis.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The not recently used (NRU) page replacement algorithm is an algorithm that favours keeping pages in memory that have been recently used.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] This algorithm works on the following principle: when a page is referenced, a referenced bit is set for that page, marking it as referenced.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Similarly, when a page is modified (written to), a modified bit is set.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The setting of the bits is usually done by the hardware, although it is possible to do so on the software level as well.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] At a certain fixed time interval, a timer interrupt triggers and clears the referenced bit of all the pages, so only pages referenced within the current timer interval are marked with a referenced bit.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Although it does not seem possible for a page to be modified yet not referenced, this happens when a class 3 page has its referenced bit cleared by the timer interrupt.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The NRU algorithm picks a random page from the lowest category for removal.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] So out of the above four page categories, the NRU algorithm will replace a not-referenced, not-modified page if such a page exists.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Note that this algorithm implies that a modified but not-referenced (within the last timer interval) page is less important than a not-modified page that is intensely referenced.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] NRU is a marking algorithm, so it is ${\tfrac {k}{k-h+1}}$ -competitive.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The simplest page-replacement algorithm is a FIFO algorithm.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The first-in, first-out (FIFO) page replacement algorithm is a low-overhead algorithm that requires little bookkeeping on the part of the operating system.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The idea is obvious from the name – the operating system keeps track of all the pages in memory in a queue, with the most recent arrival at the back, and the oldest arrival in front.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] When a page needs to be replaced, the page at the front of the queue (the oldest page) is selected.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] While FIFO is cheap and intuitive, it performs poorly in practical application.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Thus, it is rarely used in its unmodified form.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] This algorithm experiences Bélády's anomaly.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] In simple words, on a page fault, the frame that has been in memory the longest is replaced.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] FIFO page replacement algorithm is used by the OpenVMS operating system, with some modifications.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Partial second chance is provided by skipping a limited number of entries with valid translation table references, and additionally, pages are displaced from process working set to a systemwide pool from which they can be recovered if not already re-used.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] FIFO is a conservative algorithm, so it is ${\tfrac {k}{k-h+1}}$ -competitive.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] A modified form of the FIFO page replacement algorithm, known as the Second-chance page replacement algorithm, fares relatively better than FIFO at little cost for the improvement.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] It works by looking at the front of the queue as FIFO does, but instead of immediately paging out that page, it checks to see if its referenced bit is set.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] If it is not set, the page is swapped out.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Otherwise, the referenced bit is cleared, the page is inserted at the back of the queue (as if it were a new page) and this process is repeated.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] This can also be thought of as a circular queue.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] If all the pages have their referenced bit set, on the second encounter of the first page in the list, that page will be swapped out, as it now has its referenced bit cleared.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] If all the pages have their reference bit cleared, then second chance algorithm degenerates into pure FIFO.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] As its name suggests, Second-chance gives every page a "second-chance" – an old page that has been referenced is probably in use, and should not be swapped out over a new page that has not been referenced.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Clock is a more efficient version of FIFO than Second-chance because pages don't have to be constantly pushed to the back of the list, but it performs the same general function as Second-Chance.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The clock algorithm keeps a circular list of pages in memory, with the "hand" (iterator) pointing to the last examined page frame in the list.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] When a page fault occurs and no empty frames exist, then the R (referenced) bit is inspected at the hand's location.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] If R is 0, the new page is put in place of the page the "hand" points to, and the hand is advanced one position.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Otherwise, the R bit is cleared, then the clock hand is incremented and the process is repeated until a page is replaced.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] This algorithm was first described in 1969 by Fernando J.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] CLOCK is a conservative algorithm, so it is ${\tfrac {k}{k-h+1}}$ -competitive.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The least recently used (LRU) page replacement algorithm, though similar in name to NRU, differs in the fact that LRU keeps track of page usage over a short period of time, while NRU just looks at the usage in the last clock interval.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] LRU works on the idea that pages that have been most heavily used in the past few instructions are most likely to be used heavily in the next few instructions too.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] While LRU can provide near-optimal performance in theory (almost as good as adaptive replacement cache), it is rather expensive to implement in practice.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] There are a few implementation methods for this algorithm that try to reduce the cost yet keep as much of the performance as possible.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The most expensive method is the linked list method, which uses a linked list containing all the pages in memory.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] At the back of this list is the least recently used page, and at the front is the most recently used page.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The cost of this implementation lies in the fact that items in the list will have to be moved about every memory reference, which is a very time-consuming process.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Another method that requires hardware support is as follows: suppose the hardware has a 64-bit counter that is incremented at every instruction.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Whenever a page is accessed, it acquires the value equal to the counter at the time of page access.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Whenever a page needs to be replaced, the operating system selects the page with the lowest counter and swaps it out.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Because of implementation costs, one may consider algorithms (like those that follow) that are similar to LRU, but which offer cheaper implementations.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] One important advantage of the LRU algorithm is that it is amenable to full statistical analysis.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] It has been proven, for example, that LRU can never result in more than N-times more page faults than OPT algorithm, where N is proportional to the number of pages in the managed pool.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] On the other hand, LRU's weakness is that its performance tends to degenerate under many quite common reference patterns.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] For example, if there are N pages in the LRU pool, an application executing a loop over array of N + 1 pages will cause a page fault on each and every access.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] As loops over large arrays are common, much effort has been put into modifying LRU to work better in such situations.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Many of the proposed LRU modifications try to detect looping reference patterns and to switch into suitable replacement algorithm, like Most Recently Used (MRU).
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The ARC algorithm extends LRU by maintaining a history of recently evicted pages and uses this to change preference to recent or frequent access.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] It is particularly resistant to sequential scans.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The 2Q algorithm improves upon the LRU and LRU/2 algorithm.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] By having two queues, one for hot-path items and the other for slow-path items, items are first placed in the slow-path queue and after a second access of the items placed in the hot-path items.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Because references to added items are longer hold than in the LRU and LRU/2 algorithm, it has a better hot-path queue which improves the hit rate of the cache.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] A comparison of ARC with other algorithms (LRU, MQ, 2Q, LRU-2, LRFU, LIRS) can be found in Megiddo & Modha 2004.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] LRU is a marking algorithm, so it is ${\tfrac {k}{k-h+1}}$ -competitive.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The random replacement algorithm replaces a random page in memory.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] This eliminates the overhead cost of tracking page references.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Usually it fares better than FIFO, and for looping memory references it is better than LRU, although generally LRU performs better in practice.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] OS/390 uses global LRU approximation and falls back to random replacement when LRU performance degenerates, and the Intel i860 processor used a random replacement policy (Rhodehamel 1989).
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The not frequently used (NFU) page replacement algorithm requires a counter, and every page has one counter of its own which is initially set to 0.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] At each clock interval, all pages that have been referenced within that interval will have their counter incremented by 1.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] In effect, the counters keep track of how frequently a page has been used.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Thus, the page with the lowest counter can be swapped out when necessary.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The main problem with NFU is that it keeps track of the frequency of use without regard to the time span of use.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Thus, in a multi-pass compiler, pages which were heavily used during the first pass, but are not needed in the second pass will be favoured over pages which are comparably lightly used in the second pass, as they have higher frequency counters.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Other common scenarios exist where NFU will perform similarly, such as an OS boot-up.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Thankfully, a similar and better algorithm exists, and its description follows.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The not frequently used page-replacement algorithm generates fewer page faults than the least recently used page replacement algorithm when the page table contains null pointer values.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The aging algorithm is a descendant of the NFU algorithm, with modifications to make it aware of the time span of use.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Instead of just incrementing the counters of pages referenced, putting equal emphasis on page references regardless of the time, the reference counter on a page is first shifted right (divided by 2), before adding the referenced bit to the left of that binary number.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Page references closer to the present time have more impact than page references long ago.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] This ensures that pages referenced more recently, though less frequently referenced, will have higher priority over pages more frequently referenced in the past.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Thus, when a page needs to be swapped out, the page with the lowest counter will be chosen.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The following Python code simulates the aging algorithm.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Counters $V_{i}$ are initialized with 0 and updated as described above via $V_{i}\leftarrow (R_{i}\ll (k-1))|(V_{i}\gg 1)$ , using arithmetic shift operators.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] In the given example of R-bits for 6 pages over 5 clock ticks, the function prints the following output, which lists the R-bits for each clock tick t and the individual counter values $V_{i}$ for each page in binary representation.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Note that aging differs from LRU in the sense that aging can only keep track of the references in the latest 16/32 (depending on the bit size of the processor's integers) time intervals.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Consequently, two pages may have referenced counters of 00000000, even though one page was referenced 9 intervals ago and the other 1000 intervals ago.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Generally speaking, knowing the usage within the past 16 intervals is sufficient for making a good decision as to which page to swap out.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Thus, aging can offer near-optimal performance for a moderate price.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The basic idea behind this algorithm is Locality of Reference as used in LRU but the difference is that in LDF, locality is based on distance not on the used references.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] In the LDF, replace the page which is on longest distance from the current page.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] If two pages are on same distance then the page which is next to current page in anti-clock rotation will get replaced.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Many of the techniques discussed above assume the presence of a reference bit associated with each page.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Some hardware has no such bit, so its efficient use requires techniques that operate well without one.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] One notable example is VAX hardware running OpenVMS.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] This system knows if a page has been modified, but not necessarily if a page has been read.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Its approach is known as Secondary Page Caching.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Pages removed from working sets (process-private memory, generally) are placed on special-purpose lists while remaining in physical memory for some time.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Removing a page from a working set is not technically a page-replacement operation, but effectively identifies that page as a candidate.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] A page whose backing store is still valid (whose contents are not dirty, or otherwise do not need to be preserved) is placed on the tail of the Free Page List.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] A page that requires writing to backing store will be placed on the Modified Page List.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] These actions are typically triggered when the size of the Free Page List falls below an adjustable threshold.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Pages may be selected for working set removal in an essentially random fashion, with the expectation that if a poor choice is made, a future reference may retrieve that page from the Free or Modified list before it is removed from physical memory.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] A page referenced this way will be removed from the Free or Modified list and placed back into a process working set.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The Modified Page List additionally provides an opportunity to write pages out to backing store in groups of more than one page, increasing efficiency.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] These pages can then be placed on the Free Page List.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The sequence of pages that works its way to the head of the Free Page List resembles the results of a LRU or NRU mechanism and the overall effect has similarities to the Second-Chance algorithm described earlier.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Another example is used by the Linux kernel on ARM.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The lack of hardware functionality is made up for by providing two page tables – the processor-native page tables, with neither referenced bits nor dirty bits, and software-maintained page tables with the required bits present.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The emulated bits in the software-maintained table are set by page faults.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] In order to get the page faults, clearing emulated bits in the second table revokes some of the access rights to the corresponding page, which is implemented by altering the native table.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The unified page cache operates on units of the smallest page size supported by the CPU (4 KiB in ARMv8, x86 and x86-64) with some pages of the next larger size (2 MiB in x86-64) called "huge pages" by Linux.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The pages in the page cache are divided in an "active" set and an "inactive" set.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] In the basic case, when a page is accessed by a user-space program it is put in the head of the inactive set.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] When it is accessed repeatedly, it is moved to the active list.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] Linux moves the pages from the active set to the inactive set as needed so that the active set is smaller than the inactive set.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] When a page is moved to the inactive set it is removed from the page table of any process address space, without being paged out of physical memory.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] When a page is removed from the inactive set, it is paged out of physical memory.
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The size of the "active" and "inactive" list can be queried from `/proc/meminfo` in the fields "Active", "Inactive", "Active(anon)", "Inactive(anon)", "Active(file)" and "Inactive(file)".
[src:online-algorithms/page-replacement-algorithm] The working set of a process is the set of pages expected to be used by that process during some time interval.
[src:online-algorithms/ski-rental-problem] In computer science, the **ski rental problem** is a name given to a class of problems in which there is a choice between continuing to pay a repeating cost or paying a one-time cost which eliminates or reduces the repeating cost.
[src:online-algorithms/ski-rental-problem] Many online problems have a sub-problem called the rent-or-buy problem.
[src:online-algorithms/ski-rental-problem] Given an expensive up front cost, or a less expensive repeating cost, with no knowledge of how the future will play out, at what point is it better to pay the up front cost to avoid a continued repeating cost?
[src:online-algorithms/ski-rental-problem] Consider a person who decides to go skiing, but for an undecided number of days.
[src:online-algorithms/ski-rental-problem] Renting skis costs $1 per day, whereas buying a pair of skis costs $10.
[src:online-algorithms/ski-rental-problem] If the person knows in advance how many days they want to ski, then the breakeven point is 10 days.
[src:online-algorithms/ski-rental-problem] Fewer than 10 days, renting is preferable, whereas with more than 10 days, buying is preferable.
[src:online-algorithms/ski-rental-problem] However, with no advance knowledge of how long one will be skiing, the breakeven point is unclear.
[src:online-algorithms/ski-rental-problem] A good algorithm will minimize the ratio of the cost when the number of days is known in advance to the cost when the number of days is not known in advance.
[src:online-algorithms/ski-rental-problem] Ski rental is one example of this class of problem.
[src:online-algorithms/ski-rental-problem] The break-even algorithm instructs one to rent for 9 days and buy skis on the morning of day 10 if one is still up for skiing.
[src:online-algorithms/ski-rental-problem] If one has to stop skiing during the first 9 days, it costs the same as what one would pay if one had known the number of days one would go skiing.
[src:online-algorithms/ski-rental-problem] If one has to stop skiing after day 10, one's cost is $19 which is 90% more than what one would pay if one had known the number of days one would go skiing in advance.
[src:online-algorithms/ski-rental-problem] This is the worst case for the break-even algorithm.
[src:online-algorithms/ski-rental-problem] The break-even algorithm is known to be the best deterministic algorithm for this problem.
[src:online-algorithms/ski-rental-problem] If it comes up heads, she buys skis on day eight; otherwise, she buys skis on day 10.
[src:online-algorithms/ski-rental-problem] This is an instance of a randomized algorithm.
[src:online-algorithms/ski-rental-problem] The expected cost is at most 80% more than what the person would pay if she had known the number of days she would go skiing, regardless of how many days she skis.
[src:online-algorithms/ski-rental-problem] In particular, if the person skis for 10 days, her expected cost is 1/2 [7 +10] + 1/2 [9+10] = 18 dollars, only 80% excess instead of 90%.
[src:online-algorithms/ski-rental-problem] A randomized algorithm can be understood as a composition of different algorithms, each one which occurs with a given probability.
[src:online-algorithms/ski-rental-problem] Consequently, the competitive ratio of a randomized algorithm is given by the worst value of $E_{i}$ over all given instances.
[src:online-algorithms/ski-rental-problem] In the case of the coin flipping ski-rental, we note that the randomized algorithm has 2 possible branches: If the coin comes up heads, we buy on day 8, otherwise we buy on day 10.
[src:online-algorithms/ski-rental-problem] Therefore, the competitive ratio of the randomized ski-rental coin flipping algorithm is 1.8.
[src:online-algorithms/ski-rental-problem] The best randomized algorithm against an oblivious adversary is to choose some day i at random according to the following distribution p, rent for i-1 days and buy skis on the morning of day i if one are still up for skiing.
[src:online-algorithms/ski-rental-problem] Its expected cost is at most e/(e-1) $\approx$ 1.58 times (when b tends to infinity) what one would pay if one had known the number of days one would go skiing.
